%[text] # Portfolio Analysis
%[text] March 2026
clc; clear;
%[text] ## Introduction
%[text] Due to a disjointed investment approach, my portfolio is currently a collection of miscellaneous single stocks as well as some board market ETFs. My goal in this document is to use wdiely recognized models to analyze my current portfolio, determine a more centrally planned optimized portfolio for my investing goals, and measure the rebalacning cost to switch to the optimized portfolio. My analysis is centered around the Fama-French 5-Factor Asset Pricing Model, an updated version of the origional 3-Factor Asset Pricing Model.
%[text] ## Methodology
%[text] The forecasting pipeline has four stages: estimate expected returns for each asset, estimate how those assets move together, model how volatile each asset is right now, and then simulate thousands of possible futures. Each stage feeds into the next.
%[text] #### Fama-French 5-Factor Asset Pricing Model
%[text] Rather than simply averaging an asset's past returns to guess its future, this analysis estimates expected returns by measuring how sensitive each asset is to five well-known drivers of stock returns \[1\]\[2\]. Each asset's daily excess returns (returns above the risk-free rate) are regressed against the five Fama-French factor return series:
%[text] $r\_i -R\_f =\\alpha\_i +\\beta\_i^{Mkt} (R\_m -R\_f )+\\beta\_i^{SMB} \\cdot SMB+\\beta\_i^{HML} \\cdot HML+\\beta\_i^{RMW} \\cdot RMW+\\beta\_i^{CMA} \\cdot CMA+\\epsilon\_i${"editStyle":"visual"}
%[text] The five factors capture distinct drivers of returns: the overall market premium ($Mkt-R\_f${"editStyle":"visual"}), the size effect ($SMB${"editStyle":"visual"} — small companies tend to outperform large), the value effect ($HML${"editStyle":"visual"} — cheap stocks tend to outperform expensive), the profitability effect ($RMW${"editStyle":"visual"} — profitable firms tend to outperform unprofitable), and the investment effect ($CMA${"editStyle":"visual"} — conservative firms tend to outperform aggressive spenders). The regression produces a set of betas for each asset which is essentially a fingerprint showing how much the asset moves with each factor.
%[text] The expected annual return for each asset is then:
%[text] $\\mu\_i =R\_f +\\beta\_{\\mathbf{i}}^{\\top } \\lambda${"editStyle":"visual"}
%[text] where $\\lambda${"editStyle":"visual"} is a vector of long-run factor premia (the average daily return of each factor over the full available history back to 1963), scaled to annual by multiplying by 252 trading days. This is the key insight: the betas are estimated from the asset's own (potentially short) history, but the premia come from 60+ years of data published by Kenneth French's data library. An ETF with only 3 years of data still gets a stable expected return estimate because its factor sensitivities are being priced using decades of market evidence. The alpha from the regression is intentionally dropped — the forecast assumes only that factor exposures are compensated at their historical long-run rates.
%[text] #### Covariance Estimation: Ledoit-Wolf Shrinkage
%[text] The next step is estimating how the assets move together via the covariance matrix. The naive approach is to compute the sample covariance directly from historical returns, but this matrix tends to be noisy. With many assets relative to the number of observations, the estimated correlations are unreliable and the matrix can become ill-conditioned (nearly singular), which breaks downstream optimization and simulation steps.
%[text] Ledoit-Wolf shrinkage \[3\] fixes this by blending the sample covariance $S${"editStyle":"visual"} with a simpler, more stable target matrix $F${"editStyle":"visual"}:
%[text] $\\hat{\\Sigma} =\\delta F+(1-\\delta )S${"editStyle":"visual"}
%[text] The target $F${"editStyle":"visual"} keeps each asset's individual variance intact but replaces all the pairwise correlations with the portfolio-wide average correlation. The blending weight $\\delta${"editStyle":"visual"} is computed analytically; it automatically pulls harder toward the stable target when the data is noisy (few observations, many assets) and trusts the sample more when data is plentiful. The result is a covariance matrix that is always well-behaved: invertible, positive-definite, and suitable for Cholesky decomposition in the simulation stage.
%[text] #### Volatility Modelling: GARCH(1,1)
%[text] Markets go through calm periods and turbulent periods. A GARCH(1,1) model \[4\] captures this by fitting each asset with a volatility process that remembers recent market conditions. Each asset's conditional variance evolves day by day as:
%[text] $h\_{i,t} =\\omega\_i +\\alpha\_i \\epsilon\_{i,t-1}^2 +\\beta\_i h\_{i,t-1}${"editStyle":"visual"}
%[text] Tomorrow's expected variance ($h\_t${"editStyle":"visual"}) is a blend of a long-run baseline ($\\omega${"editStyle":"visual"}), how big yesterday's surprise was ($\\alpha \\cdot \\epsilon^2${"editStyle":"visual"}), and what the variance was yesterday ($\\beta \\cdot h\_{t-1}${"editStyle":"visual"}). After a market crash, $\\epsilon^2${"editStyle":"visual"} spikes, which pushes $h\_t${"editStyle":"visual"} up, and the high $\\beta${"editStyle":"visual"} keeps it elevated for many subsequent days — exactly the clustering pattern seen in real markets. These three parameters ($\\omega ,\\alpha ,\\beta${"editStyle":"visual"}) are estimated for each asset from its historical returns. The simulation is initialized using the long-run (unconditional) variance $\\sigma^2 =\\omega /(1-\\alpha -\\beta )${"editStyle":"visual"}.
%[text] #### Monte Carlo Simulation
%[text] With expected returns, the covariance structure, and per-asset GARCH models in hand, the final stage simulates 10,000 possible futures for the portfolio. Each simulation path steps forward one trading day at a time over the full investment horizon:
%[text] 1. **Variance update:** Each asset's conditional variance is stepped forward using its GARCH equation. If the previous day saw a large shock, today's variance will be higher.
%[text] 2. **Correlated random shocks:** Independent random draws are generated and then multiplied by the Cholesky factor of the correlation matrix ($L${"editStyle":"visual"}, where $\\hat{\\Sigma} =LL^{\\top }${"editStyle":"visual"}). This ensures that the simulated shocks between assets are correlated in the same way as their historical returns. If two assets historically move together, their simulated shocks will too.
%[text] 3. **Daily returns:** Each asset's daily return combines its expected drift (from the factor model) with its GARCH-scaled random shock: $r\_{i,t} =\\mu\_i^{daily} +\\sqrt{h\_{i,t} }\\cdot z\_{i,t}^{corr}${"editStyle":"visual"}. When volatility is high, the shock term gets amplified; when volatility is low, returns stay closer to the drift.
%[text] 4. **Portfolio aggregation:** The individual asset returns are combined using the portfolio weights to get a single portfolio return for the day, which is then compounded onto the cumulative wealth path: $W\_t =(1-c)\\prod\_{s=1}^t (1+r\_{p,s} )${"editStyle":"visual"}, where $c${"editStyle":"visual"} is the cost as a percentage of the initial portfolio value to rebalance. \
%[text] The result is 10,000 simulated wealth paths. Percentile envelopes (5th, 25th, 50th, 75th, 95th) are extracted at each time step to build fan charts, and cross-sections at milestone years (e.g. 10 and 44 years) are used to compute probability estimates for specific wealth targets.
%[text] #### Risk Metrics
%[text] Each portfolio is evaluated using a combination of forward-looking simulation metrics and backward-looking historical metrics:
%[text] - **Sharpe Ratio** \[5\]: $S=(\\mu\_p -R\_f )/\\sigma\_p${"editStyle":"visual"} — how much excess return the portfolio earns per unit of volatility. Higher is better. Uses the FF5-derived expected returns.
%[text] - **Sortino Ratio:** $So=(\\mu\_p -R\_f )/\\sigma\_d${"editStyle":"visual"} — similar to Sharpe, but only penalizes *downside* volatility (returns below the risk-free rate). A portfolio with large upside swings but small downside swings will have a Sortino much higher than its Sharpe.
%[text] - **Calmar Ratio:** $C=CAGR/MaxDD${"editStyle":"visual"} — the portfolio's compound annual growth rate divided by its worst historical peak-to-trough drawdown. Measures how efficiently the portfolio recovers from its worst losses.
%[text] - **Value-at-Risk (VaR, 5%):** From the Monte Carlo simulation, the 5th percentile loss at each milestone — in 95 out of 100 simulated futures, the portfolio does better than this.
%[text] - **Conditional VaR (CVaR, 5%):** The average loss across the worst 5% of simulated outcomes — not just the boundary of the tail, but how bad things get *within* the tail. This is a more conservative measure than VaR because it accounts for the severity of worst-case scenarios, not just their threshold. \
