%[text] ### Current Portfolio
%[text] Currently, my portfolio is a mix of stocks I inherited from before I had access to my brockerage account and a mix of miscellaneosu stock picks and index ETFs I have bought since turning 18. While my portfolio has a wide swath of holdings, there is no efficient way to download all holdings in my portfolio and there weights so I manually copied the largest few holdings **(come back later there may be a way to input my entire portfolio).**
pm_curr = PortfolioModel(["MSFT" "DE" "BP" "BRK.B" "VOO" "QQQ" "VXUS"], ...
    [0.1568 0.1481 0.1012 0.06539 0.1341 0.04011 0.0801], ...
    "Title", "Current");
pm_curr.Results = analyzePortfolio(pm_curr); %[output:62797f68]
portfolios{1} = pm_curr;
%[text] ### Benchmark Portfolios
%[text] The following are a collection of commonly recommended portfolios, primarily passive index funds that will serve as a baseline for comparison.
%[text] **100% VOO**
%[text] The most commonly cited benchmark for portfolio performance is the S&P 500. VOO is a low cost index fund which tracks the S&P 500 with over \\$1.5 Trillion AUM. This will be the benchmark for all other 
pm_snp = PortfolioModel("VOO", 1, "Title", "VOO", "RebalanceCost", 0.06);
pm_snp.Results = analyzePortfolio(pm_snp); %[output:8e019d12]
portfolios{end+1} = pm_snp;
%[text] **100% VT**
%[text] VT (Vanguard Total World Stock ETF) provides pure market-cap-weighted exposure to approximately 9,000 stocks across developed and emerging markets globally, at a very low expense ratio. It serves as the "null hypothesis" baseline; the portfolio you would hold if you had no active factor views and simply wanted to own the entire world market. Including VT gives a reference point for whether any factor tilt, active weighting, or added complexity in the other portfolios translates into meaningfully better risk-adjusted outcomes. If no other portfolio outperforms VT on a Sharpe or Sortino basis, it would be the rational default choice.
pm_vt = PortfolioModel("VT", 1, "Title", "VT", "RebalanceCost", 0.06);
pm_vt.Results = analyzePortfolio(pm_vt); %[output:481775b1]
portfolios{end+1} = pm_vt;
%[text] **40% VOO | 20% QQQ | 30% VXUS | 10% AAAU (US+Intl)**
%[text] This portfolio pairs broad US market exposure (VOO), a NASDAQ-100 growth tilt (QQQM), international diversification (VXUS), and a physical gold allocation (AAAU). The 40/20/30/10 split deliberately overweights US equities relative to their global market-cap weight, reflecting the historically stronger factor premia in US markets, while VXUS preserves meaningful international exposure and currency diversification. QQQM adds a concentrated technology and growth tilt that has driven strong absolute returns historically, albeit with higher volatility. The 10% AAAU (gold) position acts as a macro hedge — gold exhibits near-zero or negative correlation with equities during drawdown periods, providing a partial buffer during recessions and risk-off environments that none of the equity-only portfolios can replicate.
pm_usintl = PortfolioModel(["VOO" "QQQ" "VXUS" "AAAU"], [0.4 0.2 0.3 0.1], ...
    "Title", "US+Intl", "RebalanceCost", 0.06);
pm_usintl.Results = analyzePortfolio(pm_usintl); %[output:9a97be60]
portfolios{end+1} = pm_usintl;
%[text] ### Proposed Portfolios
%[text] **100% AVGE**
%[text] AVGE (Avantis All Equity Markets ETF) is a factor-tilted global equity fund that systematically overweights stocks exhibiting strong value and profitability characteristics across both US and international markets. Because the FF5 model explicitly prices these same factors — HML (value) and RMW (profitability) — AVGE is structurally aligned with the return forecasts this analysis produces. Unlike a passive market-cap index, its active factor tilting is expected to generate a persistent premium over a pure benchmark without sacrificing broad diversification across thousands of holdings. As a single-ticker holding it also keeps rebalancing complexity minimal, making it a strong baseline for evaluating whether multi-asset portfolios justify their added complexity.
pm_avge = PortfolioModel("AVGE", 1, "Title", "AVGE", "RebalanceCost", 0.06);
pm_avge.Results = analyzePortfolio(pm_avge); %[output:533397bb]
portfolios{end+1} = pm_avge;
%[text] **100% DFAW**
%[text] DFAW is a competing fund to AVGE with a similair methodology. The primary difference is that DFAW may be more opinionated in their factor-tilts whereas AVGE is more systematic.
pm_dfaw = PortfolioModel("DFAW", 1, "Title", "DFAW", "RebalanceCost", 0.06);
pm_dfaw.Results = analyzePortfolio(pm_dfaw); %[output:60c59302]
portfolios{end+1} = pm_dfaw;
%[text] **80% AVGE | 7% VUG | 7% VOT | %6 VBK**
%[text] This portfolio's motivation is much the same as the 5-factor growth portfolio, however it seeks a lower overall expense ratio by combining Vanguard's large, mid, and small-cap growth ETFs. RPG has a 0.35% expense ratio while the Vanguard funds enjoy expense ratios ranging from 0.03% to 0.05%. Additionally, this portfolio provides more flexibility to the various optimizers that will be employed later due to utilizing more individual assets.
pm_5fgrowth3gf = PortfolioModel(["AVGE" "VUG" "VOT" "VBK"], [0.8 0.07 0.07 0.06], ...
    "Title", "5F+4GF", "RebalanceCost", 0.06);
pm_5fgrowth3gf.Results = analyzePortfolio(pm_5fgrowth3gf); %[output:6af319e9]
portfolios{end+1} = pm_5fgrowth3gf;
